<p><strong>Looking down, the squares sit on 4 corners — the loop turns right, forward, left, back, then repeats, climbing each time.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Modify challenge.</strong> Change <strong>one</strong> thing and <strong>predict before you run</strong> — e.g. <code>range(12)</code> → <code>range(20)</code> (taller), or each turn <code>+ 4</code> → <code>+ 6</code> (wider). Write what will change, then build it.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Level up — the ROUND spiral.</strong> The square spiral turns at <strong>4 sharp corners</strong>. To make a <strong>smooth round</strong> spiral, move around a <strong>circle</strong> with <code>cos</code> and <code>sin</code> instead:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">radius = 6
for step in range(40):
    angle = step * 0.5
    x = round(radius * cos(angle))
    z = round(radius * sin(angle))
    fill GOLD from (x, step, z) to (x + 2, step, z + 2)
</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<p>🧭 <code>cos</code> and <code>sin</code> trace a <strong>circle</strong>; <code>step</code> as the height makes the circle <strong>climb</strong> — a smooth round spiral (a helix). <code>angle</code> grows every pass, so the direction keeps turning.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Predict: will the round spiral have corners or a smooth curve? What does a bigger <code>radius</code> change?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

